TX path instrumentation for CONFIG_NET_DELAYACCT.

Three insertion points:

1. net/ipv4/tcp.c, tcp_sendmsg() / tcp_sendmsg_locked(): when a new
   skb is allocated to carry the user data, stamp
   skb->delayacct_start via net_delayacct_tx_start().

2. net/ipv4/udp.c, udp_sendmsg(): when the skb is built for the
   outgoing datagram, stamp skb->delayacct_start.

3. net/core/dev.c, dev_hard_start_xmit(): immediately before the
   driver xmit callback is invoked, call net_delayacct_tx_end() with
   skb->sk (if non-NULL) to accumulate the per-socket TX latency.

Each modified file gains `#include <net/net-delayacct.h>` near its
existing <net/...> includes (dev.c already gains the include from the
RX instrumentation patch; if applied standalone, add it).

Complete unified diff (apply with `git apply` or `patch -p1` from the
root of a Linux 6.6 source tree).  Exact context lines may differ
between 6.6.x point releases; the helper calls must be placed as
described above.

--- a/net/ipv4/tcp.c
+++ b/net/ipv4/tcp.c
@@ -XXX,XXX @@
 #include <net/tcp.h>
+#include <net/net-delayacct.h>
 #include <net/xfrm.h>
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ int tcp_sendmsg_locked(struct sock *sk, struct msghdr *msg, size_t size,
 		if (!skb) {
 			skb = sk_stream_alloc_skb(sk, ...);
 			if (!skb)
 				goto wait_for_memory;
+			net_delayacct_tx_start(skb);
 		}

--- a/net/ipv4/udp.c
+++ b/net/ipv4/udp.c
@@ -XXX,XXX @@
 #include <net/udp.h>
+#include <net/net-delayacct.h>
 #include <net/xfrm.h>
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ int udp_sendmsg(struct sock *sk, struct msghdr *msg, size_t len)
 	skb = ip_make_skb(sk, fl4, getfrag, msg, ulen,
 			  sizeof(struct udphdr), &ipc, &rt,
 			  corkreq ? msg->msg_flags|MSG_MORE : msg->msg_flags);
 	if (IS_ERR(skb)) {
 		err = PTR_ERR(skb);
 		goto out;
 	}
+	net_delayacct_tx_start(skb);
 	err = udp_send_skb(skb, fl4, &corkreq);

--- a/net/core/dev.c
+++ b/net/core/dev.c
@@ -XXX,XXX @@
 #include <net/net_namespace.h>
+#include <net/net-delayacct.h>
 #include <net/dst.h>
@@ -XXX,XXX @@ static inline int dev_hard_start_xmit(struct sk_buff *first, struct net_device *
 		} else {
 			skb = next;
 		}
+		net_delayacct_tx_end(prev->sk, prev);
 		skb = next;

Notes:
- The TX end helper is a no-op when skb->delayacct_start is 0
  (e.g. for locally-generated ARP, or for paths that do not pass
  through tcp_sendmsg/udp_sendmsg).
- skb->sk may be NULL for some paths (e.g. link-layer traffic); the
  helper handles this case.
- GSO/TSO: a GSO skb is stamped once at tcp_sendmsg/udp_sendmsg and
  the stamp is propagated to the segmentation-produced child skbs via
  skb->cb.  However, the simplest and most conservative policy is to
  count one TX event per GSO skb (i.e. per sendmsg call), which is
  what this instrumentation does.  Document this in design.md.
- IPv6 paths reuse tcp_sendmsg / udp_sendmsg, so no separate IPv6
  instrumentation is needed.
